s. The key insight is that the \\\"completed normally at 17:08 UTC\\\" note refers to an earlier run that finished before the baseline was recorded at 17:40 UTC, but the session itself is still active and continuing its work. ed2d0b5d is currently running, whereas the baseline recorded it as done at 17:08 UTC. Since 17:46 UTC is beyond that completion time, this means a new monitoring cycle has started—a change I should report. The key difference is that ed2d0b5d transitioned from \\\"done\\\" back to \\\"running,\\\" which represents a genuine state change worth noting. All the status checks are passing—stitch, confluence, and gitlab are operational, the cron jobs are running as expected, and there are no blockers. The e7885813 monitor ending and not restarting isn't a concern since the 5p progress cron is still actively checking for changes and will flag anything new. Now I'm looking back at the 17:23 UTC check to see if there were any earlier changes I missed.\\n\\nScanning through the earlier monitoring runs, the 17:23 session was still running when the state file was created at 17:40, so it was genuinely active at that point. The DTLX monitor has been consistently running since 17:06 UTC, so that's stable. The real question is whether there's been any meaningful state change since the 17:40 baseline that I should be reporting on.\\n\\nLooking at the current snapshot at 17:46 UTC, the 5p QLHV monitor has moved from \\\"done\\\" to \\\"running\\\" — it appears to have cycled and restarted, which is a change worth noting.\\n\\nNow I'm checking whether the Telegram group session is still active. The data shows it ended at 17:42 UTC, but the `updatedAt` timestamp is 17:44 UTC, which creates a timing mismatch I need to resolve.\\n\\nLooking at the baseline, the group session was marked as running at 17:40 UTC, but now it's showing as done at 17:42 UTC—that's a transition I should report. So the changes are: the QLHV monitor has restarted and is running again, and the