rent state—I've got 39 sessions total including the current one, with some marked as \\\"done\\\" and others still \\\"running,\\\" and I need to track which ones are active.\\n\\nThe baseline I set earlier shows only the critical sessions, but now I'm seeing the full picture: `cron:e7885813` ended at 17:34 UTC, while `cron:ed2d0b5d` restarted and is running, and the DTLX group session ended at 17:42 UTC. These are real changes from the baseline state. I should also check if the e7885813 cron job is configured to restart or if its termination is intentional—looking at the session history, it seems the job is consistently timing out when trying to send status updates, which might be expected behavior or something that needs adjustment.\\n\\nFor sending the report, the instructions specify returning it as plain text since the Telegram tool isn't available in the subagent runtime. I'm going to format the report clearly with the detected changes and current status so it can be delivered properly. The cron job itself might still be running and sending heartbeats even though that particular session ended, so I need to figure out if that's the expected behavior or if there's something that needs fixing. I'm seeing there are actually two separate cron jobs running—one for the 5p progress check on QLHV and another for the DTLX report, plus an agent status cron. The e7885813 job appears to have ended, but the question is whether that's a problem or just normal behavior. Let me compile the report with what I've found so far. Now I'm weighing whether to mention the e7885813 termination in the report—the instructions only ask for changes since the last check, and since it's not in the baseline state, it might be outside scope. But including it would give a fuller picture of the system's status, so I'll include it with minimal emphasis. Let me format this as plain text for the report.\\n\\nActually, I'm realizing I should double-check what the baseline really was. The cron sessio