{"type":"message","id":"99b5031a","parentId":"2c7072f1","timestamp":"2026-04-14T17:50:43.122Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The heartbeat-state.json doesn't exist. Let me look at the MEMORY.md for the last session state baseline, and also the memory/2026-04-14.md for recent state.\n\nFrom the sessions_list output, I can see:\n\nActive sessions (current at 17:49 UTC):\n1. `cron:6f3323ef` — running (5p DTLX monitor) — updatedAt 17:49:51\n2. `cron:ed2d0b5d` — running (5p QLHV monitor) — updatedAt 17:44:05\n3. `telegram:group:-5163901258` — running (DTLX/QLHV group) — updatedAt 17:45:55, endedAt 17:42 UTC\n\n\n4. `telegram:direct:6053576134` — done\n5. `cron:e7885813` — running (Agent Status to Lead) — startedAt 17:44:45, endedAt 17:54:35, updatedAt 17:48:05\n\nThe current time is 17:49 UTC, so the session still appears in the list even though it ended 5 minutes ago. Looking at the baseline state from 17:40 UTC, `cron:e7885813` was already marked as running at that point, which means it transitioned to done by 17:54 UTC.\n\nNow I need to identify what actually changed between the 17:40 baseline and the current state at 17:49 UTC. Looking at the session details: `cron:6f3323ef` is still running, `cron:ed2d0b5d` completed at 17:08 UTC but the session re-ran and ended around 17:44 UTC, and `cron:e7885813` ended at 17:54 UTC with no new instance spawned. The Telegram group session also ended at 17:42 UTC. So there are several state transitions to track here.\n\nBut wait—the instructions explicitly say the state file might not exist and to use sessions_list against the last known state from memory instead. Looking at the MEMORY.md, the last documented baseline shows `cron:ed2d0b5d` as running from the 2026-04-12 session, which is outdated. I need to check the memory/2026-04-14.md file to find a more recent baseline that matches the current timestamp.\n\nFrom the memory entry, the 16:37 UTC checkpoint showed `cron:e7885813` as running, but then the 17:33 UTC report showed a different state with three active sessions including `cron:6f3323ef`. The 17:33 report itself was running `cron:e7885813`, and now at 17:49 UTC the current state is showing `cron:6f3323ef` as running as well.\n\nSo the key change between 17:33 and now is that `cron:ed2d0b5d` has gone from done back to running—a new monitoring cycle has started. The group session and other cron jobs appear to have remained stable during this window.\n\nI also need to flag that `cron:e7885813` ended at 17:54 UTC without a new instance spawning, which is a potential blocker worth noting. And looking at the subagents spawned by the group session, I can see several are already done—`senior-backend`, `senior-frontend`, and a couple of `ui-ux-pro-max` instances—while one `ui-ux-pro-max` agent is still running.\n\nNow I'm checking whether the Telegram group session itself is still active. It shows as ended at 17:42 UTC, but the last message indicates it ran a few minutes after that. The real question is whether a new group session has been spawned since then to replace it, or if it's truly gone. Since `cron:6f3323ef` is still running and presumably handles group session monitoring, there should be something tracking whether that session ended for good or if it's been reinitialized.\n\nLooking at the baseline state at 17:33 UTC, I can see the key difference: `cron:ed2d0b5d` has transitioned from \"done\" back to \"running,\" which means a new cycle started. That's the primary change to report. I should also note the critical blocker—`cron:e7885813` ended at 17:54 UTC and hasn't respawned, which is a significant issue that needs immediate attention.\n\nThe subagent status is all green: the group session's child sessions are completed as expected, the direct session finished cleanly, and all systems are operational. The pipeline itself is healthy—no failures in the monitoring cycles—but there's an underlying infrastructure concern with the e7885813 cron job that needs investigation.\n\nNow I'm trying to parse what the 17:33 UTC agent status actually represents. The message shows a Telegram group session that's been running for about 5 hours and 51 minutes, but the timestamps don't quite line up—if it started around 12:00 UTC, it should be closer to 6 hours by 17:33 UTC, so there's some ambiguity about when that session actually began. The group session from the 5p cron actually ended and started a new one at 17:43 UTC, while the baseline was running since around 12:00 UTC. The real change to flag is the QLHV monitor restarting its cycle. I should also check on the Agent Status to Lead cron job that ended at 17:54 UTC and whether that's still running.\n\nLooking at the current time of 17:49 UTC, the e7885813 session is still active and won't end for another 5 minutes, so I'll treat it as running for now. The key state change since the 17:33 UTC baseline is that the ed2d0b5d monitor has restarted—going from done to running. I'll also note the group session transition as context and flag the e7885813 potential issue.\n\nThe pipeline is healthy, three cron sessions are active, and all MCPs are operational. I don't have a Telegram messaging tool available, so I'll just return the report as plain text since the task description says it'll be delivered automatically.\n\nGenerating report output... Looking at the session data, the baseline from 17:33 UTC shows three active sessions, but at 17:49 UTC only two are still running—the group session has ended and the e7885813 session is about to end. This is a significant change that warrants reporting, especially since the group session ending might have been intended to be temporary if it's cycling every five minutes, though I don't have visibility into whether a replacement has been spawned. I should compile the final report and update the heartbeat state accordingly. I'm tracing through the cron session details—the baseline was set at 17:33 UTC, but now at 17:49 UTC there's been a state change with the ed2d0b5d cycle completing and restarting, plus the group session ending at 17:42 UTC with no new instance spawned yet. This is worth flagging, so I'll prepare the report and update the memory file.\n\nI'm also checking the e7885813 session which ran from 17:44:45 to 17:54:35 — it's still active at 17:49 UTC but will end in about 5 minutes, so I'll note it as \"ending soon\" since the next cycle won't spawn. Now I need to verify the cron job's schedule to understand the recurrence pattern. I see there's a discrepancy between what the cron job state file recorded at 17:08 UTC versus what the sessions list shows at 17:40 UTC for the same job ID — the state file might have been outdated, or there's a new instance that started later. Let me trace through the actual session timestamps to figure out which one is current.\n\nThe safest approach is to report only the confirmed changes I've verified: the ed2d0b5d monitor started a new cycle since the 17:33 UTC baseline, and the group session ended around 17:42 UTC without respawning. The e7885813 session is still running but will terminate in about 5 minutes, which could be either expected behavior or a scheduling issue. I'll focus on these concrete observations rather than speculating about the state file discrepancies.\n\nThe pipeline itself is healthy with all three cron jobs executing successfully and no failures detected. The real concern is that Telegram delivery to the group has stopped since the session ended and hasn't restarted yet. This is a potential blocker worth flagging in the report. I'll note the session states as they appear at 17:49 UTC, then finalize the report and save it to the heartbeat state.\n\nLooking back at the 17:33 UTC baseline, the group session was running with the label \"Cron: 5p Progress Report - DTLX\" and has since ended at 17:42 UTC. The cron job itself is still running, so it's unclear if this was intentional or if a new group session should have spawned. Since the session ended well before the cron job itself finished, there's a gap in monitoring that needs clarification. I'll include this observation in the report and finalize the status now.","thinkingSignature":"e3f9123ad7f1badd1bc81d1d6bff8a9624c6720bb6122452d8103c6afb2a9227"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hwncio113qyq_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"memory/2026-04-14.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":2471,"output":1935,"cacheRead":14264,"cacheWrite":7965,"totalTokens":26635,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776189001235,"responseId":"062db14ada2f1ad8a31b36efc957bcb5"}}
